<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"><channel><title>NYT &gt; Technology</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/section/technology</link><description>Technology industry news, commentary, and analysis, with reporting on big tech, startups, and internet culture. The New York Times is a hub for conversation about news and ideas.</description><atom:link rel="self" href="https://rss.nytimes.com/services/xml/rss/nyt/Technology.xml" type="application/rss+xml" /><item><title>To Reduce Electrical Grid Strain Amid Heat Wave, Data Centers Are Ordered to Use Backup Power</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/02/business/energy-environment/electric-grid-data-centers-pjm.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/02/business/energy-environment/electric-grid-data-centers-pjm.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/02/business/energy-environment/electric-grid-data-centers-pjm.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>As triple-digit temperatures engulf much of the United States, the Trump administration wants grid managers to require the use of backup power that often goes unused.</description><dc:creator>Ivan Penn and Hilary Howard</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 02 Jul 2026 15:24:06 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">heat wave</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">heat dome</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Data center</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Electric power</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Shortages</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Air conditioning</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Energy industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Pollution</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Batteries</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">PJM Interconnection</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Energy Department</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Chris Wright</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_geo">Mid-Atlantic States (US)</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/07/02/multimedia/02biz-heat-energy-datacenter-topart01-lczt/02biz-heat-energy-datacenter-topart01-lczt-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Leah Millis/Reuters</media:credit><media:description>The energy secretary has asked grid managers to require data centers to use backup power when electrical systems are under strain during the heat wave. </media:description></media:content></item><item><title>New York Times and Other Publishers Ask Court to Penalize OpenAI</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/09/technology/new-york-times-openai.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/09/technology/new-york-times-openai.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/09/technology/new-york-times-openai.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>The Times, The New York Daily News and other media organizations accused OpenAI of withholding evidence in a lawsuit.</description><dc:creator>Cade Metz</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 09 Jul 2026 14:40:32 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">The New York Times</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">OpenAI</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Lawsuits</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Newspaper</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Copyrights</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Books</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Startup</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mass media</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Fines</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Microsoft</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">New York Daily News</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Jonathan Franzen</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">John Grisham</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">George RR Martin</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Sarah Silverman</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/07/09/multimedia/09openai-lawsuits-pbkm/09openai-lawsuits-pbkm-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Manuel Orbegozo for The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>In response to the lawsuit’s filing, OpenAI has previously denied wrongdoing, saying it respects the rights of content creators.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Meta Unveils an A.I. Image Generator</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/07/technology/meta-ai-muse-image.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/07/technology/meta-ai-muse-image.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/07/technology/meta-ai-muse-image.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>Muse Image, which can create realistic images for users on Instagram and WhatsApp, is the company’s latest attempt to catch up in the global artificial intelligence race.</description><dc:creator>Eli Tan</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 07 Jul 2026 19:50:55 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Meta</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Social Media</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Instagram</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">WhatsApp</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/07/07/business/META-AI-vacation-selfie/META-AI-vacation-selfie-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>-</media:credit><media:description>Meta Muse users can generate A.I. photos similar to those they would normally post.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Meta Launches New A.I. Model as Global Technology Race Heats Up</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/09/technology/meta-muse-spark-artificial-intelligence.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/09/technology/meta-muse-spark-artificial-intelligence.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/09/technology/meta-muse-spark-artificial-intelligence.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>For the first time, the company will offer a paid version of the service, a departure from its longtime philosophy of giving its A.I. away for free.</description><dc:creator>Eli Tan</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 09 Jul 2026 18:11:42 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Meta</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mark E Zuckerberg</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Alexandr Wang</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/07/09/multimedia/09-biz-meta-ai-whbv/09-biz-meta-ai-whbv-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600-v2.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Eric Helgas for The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>The paid product opens up a new revenue stream for Meta, which is planning to spend tens of billions of dollars on artificial intelligence this year.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>In San Francisco, Some Home Sellers Now Ask for OpenAI or Anthropic Stock</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/08/technology/san-francisco-home-sales-openai-anthropic-ipo.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/08/technology/san-francisco-home-sales-openai-anthropic-ipo.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/08/technology/san-francisco-home-sales-openai-anthropic-ipo.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>Even before OpenAI and Anthropic go public, they are distorting home sales in the San Francisco Bay Area, as people race to buy and sellers ask for stock instead of cash.</description><dc:creator>Emmy Martin</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 08 Jul 2026 14:22:38 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Anthropic</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">OpenAI</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Real Estate</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Housing</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">IPO</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mill Valley Calif</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Noe Valley</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">San Francisco</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">San Francisco Bay Area</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Sonoma County CA</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">HNWI</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Wealth</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Billionaires</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">1 Percent</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/07/05/multimedia/HOUSING-IPO-1-01-qjgw/HOUSING-IPO-1-01-qjgw-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600-v2.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Cayce Clifford for The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>San Francisco home sales in May rose 12.2 percent from a year earlier, with the median price of a single-family home climbing to $2.14 million, according to a Homes.com report.</media:description></media:content></item></channel></rss>